Troubleshooting Common Issues
SSH Connection Issues
If you cannot connect via SSH:

Check if SSH service is running:
sudo systemctl status ssh
Verify the configuration syntax:
sudo sshd -t
Check the SSH log for errors:
sudo tail -f /var/log/auth.log
fail2ban Not Working
If fail2ban is not banning IPs:

Check fail2ban status:
sudo fail2ban-client status
Verify the jail configuration:
sudo fail2ban-client get sshd logpath
Check fail2ban logs:
sudo tail -f /var/log/fail2ban.log
Script Permission Issues
If scripts are not executable:

chmod +x ~/security-scripts/*.sh
Conclusion
In this lab, you have successfully implemented comprehensive endpoint security and hardening measures on a Linux system. You accomplished the following key security objectives:

SSH Security Enhancement: You configured secure SSH access by implementing key-based authentication, disabling password authentication, changing the default port, and restricting user access. These measures significantly reduce the attack surface for remote access attempts.

Automated Intrusion Prevention: You installed and configured fail2ban to automatically detect and block malicious login attempts. This provides real-time protection against brute force attacks and reduces the load on your system from repeated failed authentication attempts.

Proactive Monitoring: You created comprehensive monitoring scripts that track SSH access attempts, system resource usage, user account changes, and other security-relevant events. These scripts provide early warning of potential security incidents.

File Integrity Monitoring: You implemented a basic file integrity monitoring system that can detect unauthorized changes to critical system files, helping to identify potential compromises or configuration drift.

Network Security: You configured a host-based firewall using UFW to control network access and reduce exposure to network-based attacks.

Automation: You set up automated execution of security checks through cron jobs, ensuring continuous monitoring without manual intervention.

These security measures work together to create a layered defense strategy that is essential for protecting endpoints in modern IT environments. The skills you have learned are directly applicable to real-world scenarios and align with industry best practices for endpoint security. Regular monitoring and maintenance of these security controls will help ensure the ongoing protection of your Linux systems against evolving threats.

Remember to regularly review and update your security configurations, monitor the alert logs, and stay informed about new security threats and mitigation techniques to maintain an effective security posture.
